5. equites sere. The reading eques gives no sense. With equiles the sense is, “ a line of vessels (arranged) some way up the stream, so as to break the force of the current, afforded the horsemen a means of crossing, with their horses for the most part close at hand, swiniming alongside, and at the same time made the water smooth sor the light boats crossing lower down.'’

XXVIII. 5. ut quemque. The order is, “ipso impetu fluminis rapiente (quemque) in alteram ripam ut vadum destituerat quemque timentem altitudinem.” The ele- phants were afraid to take the stream at once, but advanced caufiously, until the water carried them off their legs, and then the current of itself swept them to the other side.
